{{Infobox writer |image = Portrait of Jean-Louis de Lolme from Constitution de l'Angleterre (1789).jpg |caption = From ''Constitution de l'Angleterre'' (1789) |birth_date = 1740 |birth_place = [[Geneva]] |death_date = {{Death-date and age|16 July 1806|1740}} |death_place = Seewen, [[Canton of Schwyz]] |resting_place = |occupation = [[Political philosophy|Political theorist]]; writer on constitutional matters |language = French |nationality = [[Republic and Canton of Geneva#History|Genevan]] and English |subject = |notableworks = ''[[:File:Jean-Louis de Lolme, Constitution de l'Angleterre (1st ed, 1771).pdf|Constitution de l'Angleterre]]'' (''The Constitution of England'', 1771) }}
'''Jean-Louis de Lolme''' or '''Delolme'''<ref>{{cite EB9|wstitle=Delolme|volume=7|page=51}}</ref> (1740{{snd}}16 July 1806) was a [[Republic and Canton of Geneva#History|Genevan]] and British [[political philosophy|political theorist]] and writer on constitutional matters, born in the then independent Republic of [[Geneva]]. As an adult he moved to England, and became a British subject. His most famous work was ''[[:File:Jean-Louis de Lolme, Constitution de l'Angleterre (1st ed, 1771).pdf|Constitution de l'Angleterre]]'' (''The Constitution of England'', 1771), which was subsequently published in English as well. In it, de Lolme advocated a constitutional form of government enshrining the principle that monarchy, [[aristocracy]] and democracy should be balanced against each other. He also praised the element of [[representative democracy]] in the constitution, and urged an extension of [[suffrage]]. The work influenced many of the [[Founding Fathers of the United States|framers]] of the [[United States Constitution]].
==Early life== De Lolme was born in the then independent Republic of [[Geneva]] in 1740. He studied for the bar, and had begun to practise law when he was obliged to emigrate on account of a pamphlet he wrote entitled ''Examen de trois parts de droit'' (''Examination of Three Parts of Rights''), which gave offence to the authorities of the town. He took refuge in England, where he lived for several years on the meagre and precarious income derived from occasional contributions to various journals.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=970}}
==Writing career== [[File:Title page of Constitution de l'Angleterre (1789).jpg|thumb|upright|The [[title page]] of a 1789 edition of de Lolme's ''[[:File:Jean-Louis de Lolme, Constitution de l'Angleterre (1789).pdf|Constitution de l'Angleterre]]'' (''The Constitution of England'')<ref>{{citation|author=Jean-Louis de Lolme|title=[[:File:Jean-Louis de Lolme, Constitution de l'Angleterre (1789).pdf|Constitution de l'Angleterre, ou, État du gouvernement anglais, comparé avec la forme républicaine et avec les autres monarchies de l'Europe &#91;The Constitution of England, or, The State of the English Government, Compared with the Republican Form and with the Other Monarchies of Europe&#93;]]|location=Geneva|publisher=Chez Barde, Manget & Compagnie, Imprimeurs-Libraires. & se trouve à Paris, Chez Buisson, Libraire, Rue Haute-feuille, hôtel Coëtlosquet, No. 22|year=1789|oclc=27983401}}.</ref>]]
During his protracted exile in England, De Lolme made a careful study of the [[Constitution of the United Kingdom|English constitution]], the results of which he published in his ''[[:File:Jean-Louis de Lolme, Constitution de l'Angleterre (1st ed, 1771).pdf|Constitution de l'Angleterre]]'' (''The Constitution of England'', Amsterdam, 1771),{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=970}}<ref>{{citation|author=Jean-Louis de Lolme|title=[[:File:Jean-Louis de Lolme, Constitution de l'Angleterre (1st ed, 1771).pdf|Constitution de l'Angleterre]]|location=Amsterdam|publisher=Chez E. van Harrevelt|year=1771|oclc=65353904}}.</ref> of which an enlarged and improved edition in English appeared in 1775,{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=970}}<ref>{{citation|author=Jean-Louis de Lolme|title=The Constitution of England: Or, An Account of the English Government; in which it is Compared, both with the Republican Form of Government, and Occasionally with the Other Monarchies in Europe|location=London|publisher=Printed by T. Spilsbury, and sold by G. Kearsley|year=1775|oclc=265591647}}.</ref> and was several times reprinted. The work excited much interest as containing many acute observations on the causes of the excellence of the English constitution as compared with those of other countries.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=970}} However, it was termed by the [[Encyclopædia Britannica Eleventh Edition|11th edition of the ''Encyclopædia Britannica'']] (1911) as "wanting in breadth of view, being written before the period when constitutional questions were treated in a scientific manner".{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=970}}
In the book, de Lolme advocated a constitutional form of government enshrining the principle of balanced government, balancing the one, the few, and the many, or the ideas of monarchy, [[aristocracy]], and democracy. He criticised the power of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|British parliament]] and made a grotesque expression which became proverbial: "parliament can do everything but make a woman a man and a man a woman". Nonetheless, de Lolme extolled the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] because, in his view, which was influenced by his own observations and study as well as by the previous writings of [[Voltaire]] and [[Montesquieu]], the [[uncodified constitution|unwritten constitution]] of the United Kingdom embodied the ideal of balanced government better than any other government of the time. In particular, he praised the element of [[representative democracy]] in the constitution, and urged an extension of [[suffrage]]. De Lolme developed and refined his political thinking to a large extent in opposition to the more radical theory of [[direct democracy]] advocated by his compatriot, [[Jean-Jacques Rousseau]], whom he accused of being unrealistic. De Lolme is sometimes identified as a probable candidate for being the person behind the pseudonymous political commentator [[Junius]].
De Lolme also wrote in English ''A Parallel between the English Government and the Former Government of Sweden'' (1772);{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=970}}<ref>{{citation|author=Jean-Louis de Lolme|title=A Parallel between the English Constitution and the Former Government of Sweden; Containing Some Observations on the Late Revolution in that Kingdom; and an Examination of the Causes that Secure Us against both Aristocracy, and Absolute Monarchy|location=London|publisher=Sold by [J.] Almon, Bookseller, in [[Piccadilly]]|year=1772|oclc=642244901}}.</ref> ''The History of the Flagellants'' (c. 1776),<ref>{{citation|author=Jean-Louis de Lolme|title=The History of the Flagellants or the Advantages of Discipline; Being a Paraphrase and Commentary on the Historia flagellantium of the Abbé Boileau ... By somebody who is not Doctor of the Sorbonne|location=London|publisher=Sold by M. Hingeston, Yeats and Robertson, and Fielding and Walker|year=c. 1776|oclc=85883406}}.</ref> based upon a work by [[Nicolas Boileau-Despréaux]];<ref>{{citation|author=Nicolas Boileau-Despréaux|authorlink=Nicolas Boileau-Despréaux|title=Oeuvres de Boileau Despréaux : avec des eclaircissemens historiques donnés par lui-méme, & rédigés par M. Brossette : augmentées de plusiers pieces, tant de l'auteur, qu'ayant rapport à ses ouvrages; avec des remarques & des dissertations critiques [Works of Boileau Despréaux: With Historical Elucidations Given by Himself, and Written Up by Mr. Brossette: Augmented with additional pieces, by the Author, Having Reported His Works (?); with Remarks and Critical Essays]|location=Amsterdam|publisher=Chez D. J. Changuion|year=1772|oclc=234084514}}.</ref> ''An Essay, Containing a Few Strictures on the Union of Scotland with England'' (1787);{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=970}}<ref>{{citation|author=Jean-Louis de Lolme|title=An Essay, Containing a Few Strictures on the Union of Scotland with England; and on the Present Situation of Ireland. Being an Introduction to De Foe's History of the Union|location=London|publisher=Printed for John Stockdale|year=1787|oclc=519178740}}.</ref> and one or two smaller works.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=970}}
==Later life== In 1775, de Lolme found himself compelled to accept aid from a charitable society to enable him to return home. He died at Seewen, a village in the [[Canton of Schwyz]], on 16 July 1806.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=970}}
==Legacy== De Lolme's ''Constitution de l'Angleterre'', along with a translation of [[David Hume]]'s ''[[The History of England (Hume)|History of England]]'' (1754–1761), supplied philosophers of the time with most of their ideas about the English constitution. It was therefore used somewhat as a political pamphlet.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=970}} The work influenced many of the [[Founding Fathers of the United States|framers]] of the [[United States Constitution]]. One Founding Father who was not present in Philadelphia, but whose ''Defence of the Constitutions of Government of the United States'' (1787)<ref>{{citation |author=John Adams|authorlink=John Adams|title=A Defence of the Constitutions of Government of the United States of America. [A reply to Turgot's "Lettre au Docteur Price sur les législations américaines."]|location=Philadelphia, Penn.|publisher=Hall & Sellers, ''etc.''|year=1787|oclc=556734150}}.</ref> influenced the delegates there, was [[John Adams]], who praised De Lolme's book as one of the best on the subject of constitutionalism ever written. Some have argued that De Lolme's work also influenced the [[Constitution of Norway]].{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}
==Selected works== *{{citation|ref=none|title=[[:File:Jean-Louis de Lolme, Constitution de l'Angleterre (1st ed, 1771).pdf|Constitution de l'Angleterre &#91;The Constitution of England&#93;]]|location=Amsterdam|publisher=Chez E. van Harrevelt|year=1771|oclc=65353904}}. Later editions: **{{citation|ref=none|title=The Constitution of England: Or, An Account of the English Government; in which it is Compared, both with the Republican Form of Government, and Occasionally with the Other Monarchies in Europe|location=London|publisher=Printed by T. Spilsbury, and sold by G. Kearsley|year=1775|oclc=265591647}}. **{{citation|ref=none|title=[[:File:Jean-Louis de Lolme, Constitution de l'Angleterre (1789).pdf|Constitution de l'Angleterre, ou, État du gouvernement anglais, comparé avec la forme républicaine et avec les autres monarchies de l'Europe &#91;The Constitution of England, or, The State of the English Government, Compared with the Republican Form and with the Other Monarchies of Europe&#93;]]|location=Geneva|publisher=Chez Barde, Manget & Compagnie, Imprimeurs-Libraires. & se trouve à Paris, Chez Buisson, Libraire, Rue Haute-feuille, hôtel Coëtlosquet, No. 22|year=1789|oclc=27983401}}. **{{citation|ref=none|author=Jean-Louis de Lolme|editor=David Lieberman|title=The Constitution of England|url=http://lf-oll.s3.amazonaws.com/titles/2089/DeLolme1449_Bk.pdf|format=PDF|location=Indianapolis, Ind.|publisher=[[Liberty Fund]]|year=2007|isbn=978-0-86597-465-4}}. *{{citation|ref=none|title=A Parallel between the English Constitution and the Former Government of Sweden; Containing Some Observations on the Late Revolution in that Kingdom; and an Examination of the Causes that Secure Us against both Aristocracy, and Absolute Monarchy|location=London|publisher=Sold by [J.] Almon, Bookseller, in [[Piccadilly]]|year=1772|oclc=642244901}}. *{{citation|ref=none|title=The History of the Flagellants or the Advantages of Discipline; Being a Paraphrase and Commentary on the Historia flagellantium of the Abbé Boileau ... By somebody who is not Doctor of the Sorbonne|location=London|publisher=Sold by M. Hingeston, Yeats and Robertson, and Fielding and Walker|year=c. 1776|oclc=85883406}}. *{{citation|ref=none|title=An Essay, Containing a Few Strictures on the Union of Scotland with England; and on the Present Situation of Ireland. Being an Introduction to De Foe's History of the Union|location=London|publisher=Printed for John Stockdale|year=1787|oclc=519178740}}.
